My Mother used to say, "to be a good conversationalist, you have to be a good LISTENER" /   Mother was right.

I have been drilling this into my kindergarteners heads. We talk about listening attentively and what that means to include thinking about what they are hearing. They even use the word attentively. It's great. I ask them if they are listening attentively, and when they realize that they aren't, they correct themselves.

Some people do not listen to a thing, they are too busy thinking of what they are going to blab next .... they dont even respond,  getting ready to run their loud mouths all the time ... after a while, why talk to them, its only a MONOLOGUE
That's only true when we listen at all. Most people are too busy with their electronic devices, to even know that you are there. Put down the phones, and have an actual conversion.
So many people do this. They only hear what's being said instead of listening to what's being said. You ask what's the difference??  U hear a noise, u listen to find out what the noise is!!
This is so true. After visiting the ear doctor he disclosed to us "Neither of you have a hearing problem, you both have a listening problem".  We're trying to do better,  lol.
I have to admit I've been guilty of this from time to time.  I now make a conscious effort to make sure I'm listening to what's being said before I reply.

I have remanded quite a few people who work in the vet's office,the doctor's office, the chiropractor's office and many more that they must speak more slowly, succinctly and with volume so we understand them.  When people make a recording they talk too fast and with the above characteristics.  Communication skills have gone downhill.

If we arent listening to understand then there is no point in listening! Reply are just the simple acknowledgement to let someone know our ears are open on the subject. Sorry if you don't agree with what I have to say.

This is true in in my case. I,m  usually thinking of the next joke to tell or what can I tell to top the subject that was related and try to change the subject to what I knew.I am just discovering this at the age of 71. I have never listened attentavely. I have retained a lot of knowledge but want to share more than listen.
Lena Marie Westphal  this reminds me of a conversation we once had about the people that wait for you to quit talking so they can start.

Replying notes that you actually are listening.
